    regional_period_notes:
      "Coin-operated electronic gaming entertainment form. Date envelope: c. 1970-present American use, with form_emergence at c. 1970 marking the transition from pinball-only and mechanical-amusement-only commercial arcade environments to electronic-video-game arcades. Peak popularity c. 1980-1995 corresponds to the 'Golden Age of Arcade Games' and subsequent home-console transition. Major manufacturers and producers spanned Atari, Bally Midway, Namco (Japan/US), Williams, Capcom, Sega — international production with substantial American commercial distribution. Standing upright cabinets dominated commercial arcade siting; cocktail and driving subtypes served bar/lounge and immersive-simulation contexts respectively. Post-1995 decline reflects home gaming console competition (Sony PlayStation, Nintendo, Microsoft Xbox) and reduced commercial arcade siting. Contemporary 'barcade' revival from c. 2005 forward has restored arcade cabinet commercial siting in bar/lounge contexts, plus retro/replica home market emergence. Construction evidence (cabinet artwork, monitor type — CRT vs LCD, control hardware, manufacturer plates, ROM board generation) reliably dates within manufacturer model histories.",
