    regional_period_notes:
      "Benches span the full range of American furniture history, but their identity varies sharply by context, material, and use. Vernacular and rural bench production appears from the earliest colonial period in farm, kitchen, hall, meeting, and work settings. Seventeenth- and eighteenth-century examples may be simple plank, trestle, joined, or settle-like forms, often locally made and utilitarian. Institutional seating expands through churches, schools, civic rooms, courtrooms, meeting houses, depots, and public waiting areas; church-specific row seating should route to form_pew rather than generic bench when pew structure or context is present. Garden and park benches expand especially from the nineteenth century with cast iron, wrought iron, stone, concrete, and slatted outdoor production. Hall benches and storage benches expand strongly from c. 1850 with Victorian, Eastlake, Aesthetic Movement, Golden Oak, Arts and Crafts, and Colonial Revival decorator vocabulary. Piano bench standardization strengthens from c. 1880 onward with the expansion of domestic piano ownership, and lift-top sheet-music storage is a strong functional indicator. Upholstered bed-end, vanity, foyer, and decorative benches expand from c. 1900 with bedroom-suite culture, Hollywood Regency decorator vocabulary, mid-century interior design, and contemporary transitional interiors. Modern minimalist, Scandinavian-influenced, industrial, and farmhouse bench production continues from c. 1945 to present. Watch for: (a) settle vs bench distinction depends on enclosure and back dominance; high panel back, enclosed sides, and box-like architectural massing point toward settle, while lower, open, or backless forms remain bench; (b) storage bench vs storage chest distinction depends on seating-first versus storage-first design intent; a comfortable, accessible, seat-height top supports bench, while deep storage volume, trunk hardware, and seating-as-incidental use support chest; (c) outdoor bench identity should be supported by materials, slatted drainage, exterior finish, rust, weathering, stone/concrete construction, or outdoor joinery, not by current placement alone; (d) pew is not a bench subtype in this architecture because institutional or religious row seating is structurally and contextually distinct enough for its own canonical form_pew; (e) form_bench_utility remains a separate canonical for narrow utility-context benches including mudroom, built-in, work, shop, boot-room, or heavy-duty utility examples; general parlor, hall, dining, piano, storage, window, garden, school, institutional, and upholstered benches route to form_bench; (f) upholstered benches require separating frame date from upholstery date because cushions, fabric, padding, skirts, and dust covers are commonly replaced; (g) current location should not control identification by itself, since benches are easily moved and often repurposed.",
