      "'Sofa,' 'couch,' 'davenport,' 'divan,' 'settee,' and 'loveseat' are frequently interchanged in retail, regional, and historical usage. Classification should depend on size, depth, upholstery, multi-user behavior, back support, arm/enclosure structure, and lounge posture rather than the seller's word. Sofa-like forms appear in America by the eighteenth century, but many eighteenth- and early-nineteenth-century examples are closer to what modern classification may call settee, canapé, or formal parlor seating. American upholstered sofa identity strengthens through Federal, Empire, Victorian parlor, Rococo Revival, Renaissance Revival, Eastlake, Aesthetic Movement, Arts and Crafts, Colonial Revival, Art Deco, Hollywood Regency, mid-century modern, late twentieth-century comfort furniture, and contemporary sectional production. Victorian sofas may show exposed carved frames, serpentine backs, tufting, horsehair, coil springs, rosewood, walnut, mahogany, or laminated curved wood depending on period and quality. Arts and Crafts examples may have exposed oak frames, slats, leather, and settle-like massing. Colonial Revival examples frequently revive camelback, Chippendale, Hepplewhite, Sheraton, and Federal forms, often with later machine construction. Mid-century sofas often use lower profiles, exposed legs, lighter frames, foam, cleaner lines, and designer-influenced proportions. Contemporary sofas increasingly include modular sectional systems, recliner mechanisms, sleeper mechanisms, cupholder consoles, power headrests, USB modules, performance fabrics, and oversized proportions. Upholstery and cushions may be much newer than the frame; separate frame date from upholstery date. Watch for: (a) sectional date floor c. 1940 anti-back-classification; (b) sleeper sofa date floor c. 1899; (c) chesterfield as a denominational style-marker, especially button-tufting plus rolled arms plus leather, but not exclusive because non-chesterfield sofas may also be tufted; (d) loveseat as a sofa subtype, not an independent parent form; (e) parlor-suite components should not be mistaken for sectionals; (f) sofa table cousin-form association, where form_sofa_table is a long narrow table designed for placement behind a sofa and should not be confused with sofa seating; (g) 'davenport' may refer to a sofa regionally or to a writing desk in another furniture category, so image evidence controls; (h) settee-vs-sofa calls should privilege depth, posture, cushion system, and lounge comfort over seller terminology.",
