    regional_period_notes:
      "The recliner should not be back-classified before the modern American mechanical recliner form emerges c. 1928. The La-Z-Boy emergence anchor is useful because it marks the beginning of the recognizable mass-market reclining lounge chair category, but it does not mean every post-1928 recliner is La-Z-Boy. Earlier adjustable seating belongs under Morris chair, invalid chair, adjustable-back lounge chair, patent chair, or other mechanical seating depending on structure. Early and mid-twentieth-century recliners may show visible levers, heavy wood or metal linkages, spring mechanisms, simple upholstered forms, and brand labels from La-Z-Boy, Stratolounger, Berkline, Lane, Barcalounger, Kroehler, Flexsteel, and other makers. Late twentieth-century recliners expand into wall-hugger, rocker recliner, swivel recliner, glider recliner, lift chair, and power recliner categories. Contemporary recliners often include power headrests, lumbar support, heat, massage, USB charging, cup holders, storage consoles, home-theater modules, faux leather, bonded leather, microfiber, performance fabric, and oversized foam-filled construction. Watch for: (a) post-1928 form-emergence boundary is hard for modern recliner identity; (b) power and lift mechanisms are post-1980 dating anchors in ordinary American consumer furniture; (c) upholstery style can imitate earlier wing, club, or traditional chair forms, so mechanism evidence must control; (d) underside inspection is often necessary because decorator recliners may hide handles and linkages; (e) a chair with a separate ottoman is not a recliner unless the chair itself reclines mechanically; (f) Morris chairs and adjustable-back lounge chairs can be misread as recliners, especially when upholstered; (g) lift recliners and invalid chairs overlap, so classify by dominant purpose and mechanism; (h) labels, mechanism patents, fasteners, foam, wiring, motor style, remote controls, and underside frame construction are the strongest dating evidence.",
