    regional_period_notes:
      "Stools are among the broadest and longest-running compact seating/support forms in American furniture. Early colonial, vernacular, and joined stools include joint stools, low stools, three-legged stools, hearth stools, and rural utility stools. Seventeenth- and eighteenth-century examples require construction evidence because later Colonial Revival and reproduction stools are common. Nineteenth-century stool use expands through piano stools, vanity stools, work stools, shop stools, industrial stools, saloon stools, and commercial counter seating. Arts and Crafts and Mission vocabulary often uses 'tabouret' for small stools or stool-like stands; this term should be read carefully because some tabourets are closer to stands or small tables. Counter and bar stools strengthen with saloon, soda-fountain, lunch-counter, diner, laboratory, factory, and later domestic kitchen-island use. Twentieth-century production adds chrome, tubular steel, cast iron, molded plywood, molded plastic, vinyl upholstery, adjustable screw mechanisms, swivel plates, foot rings, drafting-height forms, and casters. Contemporary stools include kitchen island stools, saddle stools, minimalist stools, molded plastic stools, metal industrial revival stools, adjustable-height stools, and outdoor stools. Watch for: (a) height thresholds matter strongly; (b) a backless elevated form should not be treated as a bar chair unless meaningful back support is present; (c) form_milking_stool retains specialty canonical and should not be collapsed into the general stool entry when dairy/work evidence is strong; (d) form_bar_chair routes for backed bar stools; (e) piano stool vs piano bench depends on compact single-user round or screw-height stool identity versus elongated bench identity; (f) tabouret may be stool, stand, or small table depending on construction and use; (g) upholstered vanity stools can be confused with ottomans, tuffets, or slipper chairs, so back support, softness, height, and dressing-table context matter; (h) outdoor stool use should be dated by material, finish, fasteners, drainage, weathering, and construction rather than current patio placement alone; (i) swivel, screw-height, cast-iron, chrome, molded plastic, and adjustable mechanisms are useful dating evidence but should not override form identity.",
