      "American tilt-top tables emerge with eighteenth-century tea culture and small parlor-service furniture, especially c. 1730-1800. Strong original-period production is associated with Philadelphia, New England, New York, Newport/Rhode Island, and other cabinetmaking centers, with regional variation in pedestal turning, foot form, carving, proportions, woods, and hardware. Mahogany is common in high-style examples, while cherry, maple, walnut, birch, and other regional woods may appear in provincial or later examples. Colonial Revival reproduction is extremely common c. 1880-1940 and continues afterward, often imitating eighteenth-century silhouettes, tripod bases, birdcage construction, piecrust edges, and Chippendale vocabulary. Do not date a tilt-top table as eighteenth century from form alone. Construction evidence is required: hand-planed surfaces, oxidation continuity, appropriate hinge and latch hardware, screw type, underside wear, battens or cleats, top-to-base consistency, tool marks, wood selection, carving quality, joinery, repairs, and wear patterns. Watch for: (a) married tops and bases; (b) replaced catches or hinges; (c) later screws in old holes; (d) reproduction birdcage assemblies; (e) artificially aged surfaces; (f) cut-down or altered pedestal tables; (g) candle stands misclassified as tea tables; (h) fixed pedestal tables misclassified as tilt-top because of seller language; (i) piecrust edge over-attribution without construction proof; (j) Colonial Revival examples that are honestly old but not eighteenth century. The mechanism is the primary form evidence; the date must be resolved through construction and material evidence.",
