    notes: "Per appraiser authoring 2026-05-17. Gateleg table earns its own canonical entry rather than remaining only a subtype within form_drop_leaf_table because the swinging gate-like leg assemblies are a structurally distinctive support mechanism with specific period origins, strong revival production, and meaningful dating implications. The form emerges in late seventeenth-century English production, broadly c. 1670, and appears in American colonial furniture by c. 1700. A gateleg table is a drop-leaf table whose leaves are supported by one or more hinged swinging leg-and-stretcher frames, rather than only by brackets, fly rails, slides, or fixed supports. It overlaps with form_drop_leaf_table because every gateleg is a drop-leaf table; form_dining_table because large examples function as dining tables; form_kitchen_table because many utilitarian examples are kitchen-scaled; form_breakfast_table because compact examples may serve informal meals; form_tea_table and form_occasional_table because small examples often serve light service or parlor use; and Sutherland table, butterfly table, Pembroke table, and other drop-leaf variants. Because Colonial Revival, English import, and twentieth-century reproduction examples are common, early-period attribution must rely on construction, hinges, wear, turnings, secondary woods, oxidation, tool marks, joinery, and fasteners rather than silhouette alone. Diagnostic identity rests on 10 canonical distinguishing features and 8 documented subtypes.",
