    regional_period_notes:
      "Gateleg tables emerge in late seventeenth-century English furniture, broadly c. 1670, and are associated with late Stuart, William and Mary, and early eighteenth-century expandable table traditions. American production begins around c. 1700, with colonial examples influenced by English prototypes but substantially rarer than later revival pieces. Early examples may use oak, maple, walnut, cherry, pine secondary woods, pegged construction, hand-planed surfaces, hand-cut joinery, early hinges, and period-appropriate wear. Large numbers of gateleg tables encountered in the American market are Colonial Revival, English revival, imported, or later traditional reproductions, especially c. 1880-1940 and continuing afterward. Barley-twist examples are especially vulnerable to overdating because spiral turning was widely revived. Construction evidence should drive dating: hinge type, screw type, leaf joint, rule joint, gate wear arcs, oxidation, pegging, stretcher joinery, underside surfaces, tool marks, wood selection, finish, and whether the gate assemblies are original. Watch for: (a) drop-leaf tables misidentified as gatelegs without true swinging gate supports; (b) butterfly tables misread as gatelegs; (c) Pembroke tables overcalled as gatelegs; (d) Sutherland tables collapsed into gateleg identity; (e) twentieth-century Colonial Revival pieces misidentified as colonial originals; (f) married leaves, replaced gates, or altered hinges; (g) modern reproduction barley-twist turnings; (h) dining function used to override the mechanical form; (i) excessive reliance on seller terms such as 'Colonial' or 'Jacobean'; (j) imported English revival tables mistaken for American colonial production.",
