    regional_period_notes:
      "Trestle construction has very old roots in medieval and European table forms, but American attribution requires careful separation between early construction, nineteenth-century vernacular or work use, revival furniture, and modern farmhouse production. In the American market, most encountered trestle tables are not early colonial or medieval survivals; they are more often Arts and Crafts/Mission c. 1900-1925, Jacobean Revival/Tudor Revival c. 1900-1940, institutional or library furniture c. 1900-1950, rustic/farmhouse production c. 1900-present, or modern decorator farmhouse furniture c. 1990-present. Arts and Crafts examples often emphasize rectilinear oak construction, through-tenon or wedge-key effects, heavy stretchers, and visible joinery. Jacobean and Tudor Revival examples often use dark finishes, bulbous turnings, carved stretchers, refectory proportions, and dining-suite context. Farm and work trestle tables may show plank tops, scrubbed surfaces, painted bases, heavy wear, repairs, knife marks, stains, replaced boards, and utilitarian construction. Modern farmhouse pieces often show intentional distressing, thick-looking engineered tops, X-bases, metal fasteners, gray or brown stains, and contemporary screw/bolt construction. Watch for: (a) heavy appearance mistaken for early date; (b) refectory, monastery, Jacobean, or Tudor sales language overdating twentieth-century revival furniture; (c) through-tenon or pegged effects that are decorative rather than structural; (d) modern farmhouse distressing mistaken for honest age; (e) four-leg farm tables misclassified as trestle tables; (f) pedestal tables with round or double pedestal supports mislabeled as trestle without a true stretcher system; (g) benches misread as low trestle tables; (h) draw-leaf expansion mistaken for gateleg or extension-table identity; (i) replaced plank tops or married bases; (j) institutional tables misread as domestic antiques. For pre-1880 American attribution, require construction evidence such as hand-cut mortise-and-tenon joints, appropriate pegging, riven or hand-planed stock, oxidation continuity, period fasteners, regional wood consistency, wear in logical locations, and absence of modern machine distressing.",
