    regional_period_notes:
      "Parlor tables are strongly associated with American Victorian, Rococo Revival, Renaissance Revival, Eastlake, Aesthetic Movement, and Golden Oak Era production, broadly c. 1850-1915. They belong to the formal parlor and sitting-room culture of nineteenth-century American homes, where small decorative tables supported lamps, albums, vases, photographs, statues, refreshments, calling-card trays, and display objects. A strong matched-parlor-suite tradition exists, especially with sofa, settee, side chairs, armchairs, rocker, étagère, whatnot, pier mirror, or other parlor furniture. Walnut dominates much mid-Victorian production; rosewood and mahogany appear in higher-style examples; oak, especially flat-sawn or quarter-sawn, becomes especially prominent in Golden Oak Era production. Marble tops are important clues for many higher-style examples, but marble is often replaced, recut, or married, so check top fit, edge profile, underside support, color, overhang, wear, and base design. Watch for: (a) parlor table vs center table, where scale and central-room function distinguish the forms; (b) parlor table vs side or lamp table, where parlor-suite vocabulary and period identity matter; (c) Eastlake and Aesthetic Movement overlap, where incising and geometry may be shared but Aesthetic examples often show stronger surface-design or Japanese-influenced vocabulary; (d) Golden Oak Era examples being described as a style rather than an era or market category; (e) Colonial Revival, Victorian Revival, and twentieth-century decorator reproductions c. 1920-1940 and later; (f) modern Victorian-style accent tables with imported carving or reproduction marble tops; (g) marble tops married to unrelated bases; (h) center tables cut down or misdescribed as parlor tables; (i) plant stands or fern stands misread as parlor tables; (j) occasional tables overclassified as parlor tables without period construction evidence. Period dating should rely on construction, underside oxidation, fasteners, joinery, wood, veneer, carving method, caster type, finish, maker labels, suite context, and wear continuity.",
