      "Bistro/café terminology is often modern retail language, but the compact commercial dining and drink-table form has meaningful late nineteenth- and twentieth-century roots. In American identification, early diagnostic examples include cast-iron-base café, soda-fountain, ice-cream parlor, and commercial dining tables broadly c. 1880-1930, often with marble, stone, wood, or later replacement tops. Folding metal and wood-slat café tables become especially common from the early twentieth century onward and remain standard patio, sidewalk, and hospitality furniture. Domestic bistro and dinette-scale examples become especially common with twentieth-century kitchen planning, apartment living, patios, and casual dining, especially c. 1920-present. Modern bistro/café tables from c. 1980-present range from outdoor patio standards to commercial restaurant equipment and designer hospitality forms. Outdoor examples may use powder-coated metal, aluminum, wrought iron, synthetic wicker, composite, stone, tile, glass, teak, acacia, eucalyptus, or weather-resistant laminate and may show fading, corrosion, paint loss, water exposure, UV damage, or outdoor fastener corrosion. Height and support structure should be captured separately because they control use classification more reliably than retail naming. Watch for: (a) modern reproductions of period cast-iron café tables; (b) confusion between dining-height, counter-height, and bar-height examples; (c) outdoor patio tables sold as 'bistro' without true café/dining scale; (d) pub tables misclassified as bistro solely because they are round; (e) breakfast tables misclassified as bistro solely because they are compact; (f) commercial restaurant equipment mistaken for antique domestic furniture; (g) marble or stone tops married to later bases; (h) replacement laminate or butcher-block tops on older commercial bases; (i) modern decorator 'French café' reproductions; (j) low cocktail or occasional tables misread as bistro without height measurement.",
